04:49.609 --> 04:59.862
Now, you know, this idea of repentance and being aware of the sin in our life, it can be something that's a little difficult.

04:59.882 --> 05:09.234
And a lot of times when we're confronted with some sin in our life or something we've done, there's a couple ways that we can respond to this.

05:09.410 --> 05:23.852
The two words I used to describe are guilt or shame and I looked this up in psychology wording how they view these things and what they said is that that actually guilt is something that can actually be very healthy.

05:24.213 --> 05:27.117
A healthy person should have some sense of guilt.

05:27.137 --> 05:30.242
Of course, if you have no guilt over anything you've done, you're a psychopath, right?

05:30.543 --> 05:31.404
We don't want to be a psychopath.

05:31.424 --> 05:32.465
It's not looking for crazy people.

05:32.485 --> 05:34.068
You might be crazy, but don't be a psychopath.

05:34.489 --> 05:38.034
So guilt is a good thing, but shame can be destructive.

05:38.594 --> 05:39.455
You know, and not good.

05:39.535 --> 05:56.822
So, you know, a good example would be is if you're leaving the church this morning and you're pulling out and you're at a stoplight, you know, and all of a sudden, you know, you didn't see it turn red and you almost go through a red light and also any car zoos and passenger, whoa, you quick hit on your brakes.

05:56.862 --> 05:59.526
So, you have a response there.

05:59.966 --> 06:01.629
You're convicted of something you did wrong.

06:02.310 --> 06:05.074
Now, the healthy guilt response is, oh my goodness,

06:05.506 --> 06:06.267
What did I do?

06:06.327 --> 06:08.270
Oh, man, I need to pay more attention.

06:08.310 --> 06:08.811
What was I doing?

06:08.831 --> 06:10.393
I almost got myself into some serious trouble.

06:10.854 --> 06:13.197
I have to make sure I'm paying attention when I'm driving, right?

06:13.698 --> 06:14.920
That is a healthy response.

06:14.980 --> 06:19.046
You saw something that was wrong and you look how can I change my life?

06:19.086 --> 06:21.068
What do I need to do to make this better?

06:21.709 --> 06:27.558
A shame response would be you go and you have that same experience, but then you just sit there and you break into tears and just, oh my goodness.

06:28.760 --> 06:30.482
I'm such an awful person.

06:30.626 --> 06:32.629
They should just take my license.

06:32.649 --> 06:33.991
I should never be allowed to drive.

06:34.011 --> 06:36.995
In fact, I should never be allowed to go anywhere ever again.

06:37.055 --> 06:39.278
That's a little intense.

06:40.119 --> 06:41.741
But that's what a shame response does.

06:41.801 --> 06:45.987
A shame response is when you make, you get this feeling of, I'm no good, I'm awful.

06:46.007 --> 06:50.413
So if you feel that, that's not healthy.

06:51.154 --> 06:55.060
The responsibility is something, oh, I need to stop what I'm doing and start doing the right thing.

06:55.420 --> 06:57.123
That is a healthy response.

06:58.344 --> 06:59.666
But we don't like that.

06:59.746 --> 07:02.088
comfortable always to have those things pointed out in us.

07:03.770 --> 07:14.040
Sometimes people, people who struggle with addictions, things that they tend to surround themselves, their friendship, the people they interact with, are also people who deal with those things.

07:14.721 --> 07:17.784
Those same addictions because they're your little enablers, right?

07:18.364 --> 07:21.908
And you kind of get around and no one's telling you not to do that.

07:22.408 --> 07:23.990
They just kind of laugh it off and what have you.

07:24.010 --> 07:25.271
